337 respondent be immediately surrendered and shall take
338 possession of the firearms and ammunition that are
339 surrendered. A law enforcement officer serving a gun violence
340 protective order may conduct a lawful search for firearms and
341 ammunition.
342 (c) At the time of surrender or removal, a law
343 enforcement officer taking possession of a firearm or
344 ammunition pursuant to a gun violence protective order shall
345 issue a receipt identifying all firearms and ammunition that
346 have been surrendered or removed and provide a copy of the
347 receipt to the respondent. Within 72 hours after serving the
348 order, the officer who served the order shall file the
349 original receipt with the court that issued the gun violence
350 protective order, and shall ensure that the law enforcement
351 agency retains a copy of the receipt.
352 (d) If a petitioner has probable cause to believe a
353 respondent to a gun violence protective order owns, controls,
354 or possesses a firearm or ammunition that the respondent has
355 failed to surrender pursuant to this section, or has received
356 or purchased a firearm or ammunition while subject to the
357 order, the petitioner may petition the court to issue a
358 warrant. The petition shall describe the firearm or ammunition
359 and where the firearm or ammunition is reasonably believed to
360 be located. The court may issue the warrant upon a finding of
361 probable cause.
362 (e) A law enforcement agency may charge the respondent
363 a fee not to exceed the reasonable and actual costs incurred
364 by the law enforcement agency for storing a firearm or
